{"id": "24709", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24709", "title": "Collect the fee for Gaelan Bayle", "text": "Collect the fee for Gaelan Bayle is a main quest which can be started in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%202\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 2&lt;/a&gt; the first time the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; enters the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Athkatla Slums&lt;/a&gt;.\nWalkthrough.\nThe first time the party leaves &lt;a href=\"Waukeen%27s%20Promenade\"&gt;Waukeen's Promenade&lt;/a&gt;, a cut scene will start showing &lt;a href=\"Jon%20Irenicus\"&gt;Jon Irenicus&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt; being brought to &lt;a href=\"Spellhold\"&gt;Spellhold&lt;/a&gt;. Then Chapter 2 immediately starts. In the Slums the party will be greeted by &lt;a href=\"Gaelan%20Bayle\"&gt;Gaelan Bayle&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Thieves\"&gt;Shadow Thief&lt;/a&gt; who will claim to know the way to Spellhold and offer to help &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; find it, if he follows him to his &lt;a href=\"Gaelan%20Bayle%27s%20Home\"&gt;home&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the privacy of his house, Gaelan will name the price for the Shadow Thieves help \u2013 . He will also suggest a &lt;a href=\"Quests\"&gt;job&lt;/a&gt; that will bring the party closer to that goal, dependent on Gorion's Ward's &lt;a href=\"Classes\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt;. Gaelan's nephew, &lt;a href=\"Brus\"&gt;Brus&lt;/a&gt; will then await the party in front of the house to give them further directions on how to start the quest. Brus will then lead the party either to the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt;, or to an exit point of the Slums.\nOnce the party has gathered at least , a &lt;a href=\"vampire\"&gt;vampire&lt;/a&gt; named &lt;a href=\"Valen\"&gt;Valen&lt;/a&gt; will appear and arrange a &lt;a href=\"Meeting%20with%20Valen%27s%20mistress\"&gt;meeting&lt;/a&gt; with the &lt;a href=\"Bodhi\"&gt;leader&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;'s vampires. Brus will also appear and say that Gaelan Bayle has news for the party. The next time the party sees Gaelan, he will lower the price to . Bodhi will also offer to arrange the trip to Spellhold for the same price - . When talking with her, the player will have to choose sides. If the proposal of Bodhi is refused and the party sides with the Shadow Thieves, it will gain 36,750 XP per party member as soon as it pays Gaelan.\nConsequences.\nChoosing to side with the Shadow Thieves will make the vampires hostile towards the party. This will eliminate all chances to work for &lt;a href=\"Bodhi\"&gt;Bodhi&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "49978", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49978", "title": "Collus Darathon", "text": "The Monk Collus Darathon is a character from and part of the &lt;a href=\"Rasaad%27s%20Journey\"&gt;Rasaad's Journey&lt;/a&gt; quest line.\nGameplay.\nCollus is ostensibly the current Heretic Temple leader of the \"Two-Fold Trust\". He is encountered when the party makes entry into the &lt;a href=\"Heretic%20Temple%20Interior\"&gt;Heretic Temple Interior&lt;/a&gt;. He will address you when you are nearby the center of the temple area. The dialogue, your questions, statements and replies will determine the direction of the quest to this point. It could lead to an immediate hostile reaction, or you could pursue beginning the initiation process and undergoing various trials of pain and penance. Rasaad is suspicious and will also provide interjections during the dialogue for you to consider. \nCollus Darthon has all the abilities, immunities and special bonuses afforded to a Dark Moon Monk, and commensurate with his 19th Level experience. Collus is not meant to be killed or destroyed as determined by the game script, and he will leave the Temple after the dialogue with the party is finished, no matter what the outcome."}
{"id": "6830", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6830", "title": "Color Spray", "text": "The Color Spray spell causes a fan-shaped spray of colors to spring forth from the caster's hand, rendering low level creatures unconscious for 5 rounds. They will not wake up upon receiving damage.\nGameplay.\nThe caster selects a designated point on the area map to aim this spell toward, using the targeting cursor to denote the spot on the map, and clicks it.\nUpon completion of the spell the caster is frozen for 1 second, as a multicolored fan shaped spray projectile launches, that spreads out 90 degrees in front of the caster with a 25 feet length.\nAny creatures within the colored spray with 4 Hit Dice or less may be affected by the spell, and a saving throw versus Spell is allowed to resist it. Contrary to the spell's description of 1d6 creatures affected, that isn't implemented in the game and is just an AD&amp;D descriptor for literary flourish from the Pen and Paper game.\nCreatures with 5 HD will show a text display reading \"Too high of level for Color Spray\".\nFailing the save results in the victim being made &lt;a href=\"Unconscious\"&gt;Unconscious&lt;/a&gt; for five rounds - they will be made &lt;a href=\"Helpless\"&gt;Helpless&lt;/a&gt; and are not revived/awakened by taking damage.\nThis spell can potentially be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; or negated completely by &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Alteration&lt;/a&gt; or a &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;.\nNote that &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elf&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Half-elf\"&gt;Half-elf&lt;/a&gt; creatures do not get their innate resistance to sleep against this spell's unconsciousness effect.\nThis spell is flagged as a \"Hostile\" attack, and will cause neutral creatures to turn hostile, as well as others in the vicinity.\nDue to the spell's HD limitation, the utility of the spell is greatly diminished after Baldur's Gate I. See the Trivia section for how the Pen and Paper AD&amp;D spell version was designed.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition \"Color Spray\" Wizard spell can cause unconsciousness, blindness or stun targets depending on the caster's level and the target's level, saving throws versus this spell are also different than the game's version. Additionally, there is no target hit dice threshold where the spell becomes unable to affect a target, it can be used against any HD level creature. See the External links for further information.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, changing its effects and scaling. See below for description:\nColor Spray\nLevel: 1\nSchool: Alteration\nRange: Special\nDuration: Special\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: Special\nSaving Throw: Spell negates\nUpon casting this spell, the wizard causes a vivid, fan-shaped spray of clashing colors to spring forth from his hand. The spray is 15 feet in length and spread out in a horizontal arc of about 60 degrees in front of the wizard. The spell\u2019s effects depend upon the caster\u2019s level - creatures with Hit Dice/levels less than or equal to the caster are slowed for 5 rounds, those with Hit Dice/levels one or two greater than the wizard are blinded for 3 rounds, and all others are confused for 1 round. Creatures with more than 22 Hit Dice/levels will have to save only against the confusion effect, regardless of the caster\u2019s level."}
{"id": "51300", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51300", "title": "Color Spray (innate)", "text": "Color Spray is an innate ability effect available to most &lt;a href=\"Radiant%20Mephit\"&gt;Radiant Mephit&lt;/a&gt; creatures in the game saga.\nEffects.\nThe spell effect is directed at a single-creature target uninterruptable and takes almost no time to deploy. A fan shaped spray projectile is launched at a single target in range. It will strike the target and any other creatures in the arc of colors may also be affected.\nAny creature in the spray must roll a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; vs. Spell or be made &lt;a href=\"Unconscious\"&gt;Unconscious&lt;/a&gt; for 5 rounds. Even damage to the creature will not revive them. A dispel magic effect can remove the effect. If made unconscious, the creature is considered under the &lt;a href=\"Helpless\"&gt;Helpless&lt;/a&gt; state.\nThe innate ability can be blocked by magic resistance and has level 1 spell power, and thus could be blocked by spell protections like &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;. However, a &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt; would be needed for creatures who are in the spell's area of effect and not the initial target. \nNote that Elves and Half-elves do not get any racial resistance to this ability, as the ability isn't considered a &lt;a href=\"Sleep%20%28Status%20Effect%29\"&gt;Sleep (Status Effect)&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "6799", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6799", "title": "Colquetle's Family Amulet", "text": "Colquetle's Family Amulet is non-magical that can be found in \"\".\nAcquisition.\nIt can be found on the\u00a0&lt;a href=\"North%20Nashkel%20Road\"&gt;North Nashkel Road&lt;/a&gt; beside three corpses just southwest of the Hobgoblin Camp. \nFunction.\nIt can be given to &lt;a href=\"Mr.%20Colquetle\"&gt;Mr. Colquetle&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt;, in the house just north of &lt;a href=\"Firebead%27s%20Home\"&gt;Firebead's Home&lt;/a&gt; for 250 XP and +1 &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt;. Saying that the party profited from his son's death, demanding payment or outright refusing to give it results in 250 XP but -1 Reputation.\nNotes.\n In the original \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\", there is no amulet on the North Nashkel Road. Instead, Mr. Colquetle will take any &lt;a href=\"Bloodstone%20Amulet\"&gt;bloodstone amulet&lt;/a&gt;, saying that it belongs to his son, but there is no reward. Colquetle's Family Amulet apparently \"is\" a bloodstone amulet, as they have identical icons."}
{"id": "31235", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31235", "title": "Combat", "text": "Combat includes the mechanics of hitting and missing, &lt;a href=\"Turn%20Undead\"&gt;turning undead&lt;/a&gt;, special ways to attack and defend, &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt;, and more.\nCombat rules are based on the use of dice rolls. Each time an action is performed in combat, the game simulates the rolling of one or more dice to determine the result. The dice roll is referred to by a code in the form: number of dice, followed by \u201cd,\u201d followed by a numeral for the type of dice. For example, one 6-sided die is \"1d6\"; five 12-sided dice are \u201c5d12.\u201d\nArmor class.\nArmor Class (AC) is the protective rating of a type of armor. &lt;a href=\"Armor\"&gt;Armor&lt;/a&gt; provides protection by reducing the chance that a character is attacked successfully (and suffers &lt;a href=\"damage\"&gt;damage&lt;/a&gt;). Armor does not absorb damage, it prevents it. Penetrating the armor of a &lt;a href=\"fighter\"&gt;fighter&lt;/a&gt; in full plate mail to cause any damage is no small task.\nArmor Class is measured on a scale from 10, the worst (no armor), to \u201310, the best (very powerful magical armors). The lower the number, the more effective the armor. &lt;a href=\"Shields\"&gt;Shields&lt;/a&gt; can also improve the AC of a character.\nHigh &lt;a href=\"dexterity\"&gt;dexterity&lt;/a&gt; gives a bonus to Armor Class.\nDamage.\nDamage is what happens to a character when an opponent attacks him successfully. Damage can also occur as a result of &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fire%20damage\"&gt;fire&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Acid%20damage\"&gt;acid&lt;/a&gt; and other &lt;a href=\"elemental%20damage\"&gt;elemental damage&lt;/a&gt; types, and anything even remotely dangerous in the real world. Damage from most attacks is measured in &lt;a href=\"hit%20point\"&gt;hit point&lt;/a&gt;s. Each time a character is hit, he suffers points of damage. It can be as little as 1 point to as many as 80 or more. These points are subtracted from the character\u2019s current hit point total. When this reaches 0, the character is dead.\nMelee.\nMelee is any situation in which characters are battling each other hand-to-hand, whether with &lt;a href=\"fist\"&gt;fist&lt;/a&gt;s, teeth, claws, swords, &lt;a href=\"axes\"&gt;axes&lt;/a&gt;, pikes, or something else. &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt; is a valuable asset in melee.\nMissile combat.\nMissile combat is defined as any time a &lt;a href=\"weapon\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt; is shot, &lt;a href=\"Throwing%20weapons\"&gt;thrown&lt;/a&gt;, hurled, or otherwise propelled. Missile and melee combat have the same basic rules, but there are special situations and modifiers that apply only to missile combat; a character's &lt;a href=\"dexterity\"&gt;dexterity&lt;/a&gt;, for example, affects their &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;chance to hit&lt;/a&gt;.\nTHAC0.\nTHAC0 is an acronym for \u201cTo Hit Armor Class 0.\u201d This is the number a character, NPC, or monster needs to attack an &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;Armor Class&lt;/a&gt; 0 target successfully. THAC0 depends on a character\u2019s &lt;a href=\"Experience\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt;. The THAC0 number is used to calculate the number needed to hit any Armor Class. THAC0 improves as the level of a character increases.\nSaving throws.\nSaving throws are measures of a character\u2019s resistance to special types of attacks \u2013 &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt;s, magic, and attacks that affect the whole body or mind of the character. The ability to make successful saving throws improves as the character increases in &lt;a href=\"Experience\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt;.\nSpeed factor.\nSpeed factors are numbers between 1 and 10. The lower the speed factor of a &lt;a href=\"weapon\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt;, the more quickly the character wielding that weapon begins their sequence of attacks.\nCasting time.\nThe casting time of a &lt;a href=\"spell\"&gt;spell&lt;/a&gt; is the amount of time the caster is busy doing the motions of casting before the spell\u2019s effects take place. Only one spell per round can be cast. Even if you cast a spell with a short casting time, you must wait until the end of the round before starting your next spell.\nThe attack roll.\nAn attack roll is a simulated twenty sided die roll (1d20) that determines whether an attack succeeds or fails. The attack is successful if the result of the die roll is equal or higher than a certain number. This number is called the \u201cto-hit\u201d number.\nAttack rolls are used for attacks with swords, &lt;a href=\"bows\"&gt;bows&lt;/a&gt;, rocks, and other &lt;a href=\"weapons\"&gt;weapons&lt;/a&gt;, as well as blows from &lt;a href=\"fist\"&gt;fist&lt;/a&gt;s, and other hand-to-hand attacks.\nThe to-hit number.\nThe to-hit number is the result of subtracting the &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;Armor Class&lt;/a&gt; of the target from the attacker\u2019s &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt;. The attacker has to roll the resulting number, or higher, on 1d20 to hit the target.\nExample: \"Rath is a 7th level fighter. His THAC0 is 14, which means that he needs to roll a 14 or better to hit a character or creature of Armor Class 0. In combat, Rath, attacking an orc wearing chainmail armor (AC 6), needs to roll an 8 (14\u20136=8) to hit the orc. An 8 or higher on 1d20 will hit the orc. If Rath hits, he rolls the appropriate dice to determine how much damage he inflicts.\"\nIn a typical game combat situation, THAC0 is modified by weapon bonuses, strength bonuses, and the like. The actual to-hit number is the result of subtracting the target\u2019s Armor Class from this modified THAC0.\nExample: \"Rath is still a 7th-level fighter. He has a Strength of 18/80, which gives him a +2 bonus to his attack roll. He fights with a long sword +1. His base THAC0 is 14, which is modified to 12 by his Strength and to 11 by his weapon. If attacking the orc from the earlier example, Rath would have to roll a 5 or higher on 1d20 in order to hit (11\u20136=5).\"\nIf the die roll on 1d20 is equal to or greater than this adjusted to-hit number, the attack succeeds. If the roll is lower, the attack fails.\nModifiers to the to-hit number.\nMany factors can modify the number a character needs for a successful hit. These variables are called modifiers to the to-hit number or to the attack roll.\nStrength Modifier: A character\u2019s strength can modify the to-hit number, altering both the chance to hit and the damage caused. This modifier is applied to melee attacks.\nMagical items: The magical properties of a weapon also attack rolls. &lt;a href=\"Item\"&gt;Item&lt;/a&gt;s that give a bonus to the attack roll or Armor Class often are identified by a plus sign. For example, a sword +1 may improve a character\u2019s to-hit number by one. A suit of chain mail +1 may improve the Armor Class of the character by one over the protection provided by a non-magical suit of chain mail. (In this case, the magical version has an AC of 4 while the non-magical one has an AC of 5). may have a negative modifier (a penalty), resulting in a subtraction from the attack roll or an addition to Armor Class.\nThere is no limit to the number of modifiers that can be applied to the to-hit number or the AC, nor is there a limit to the positive or negative number (the total of all modifiers).\nIf the target is &lt;a href=\"sleep\"&gt;sleep&lt;/a&gt;ing or held, the attack automatically hits and causes normal damage."}
{"id": "4765", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4765", "title": "Comet", "text": "Comet is a\u00a0party friendly &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; usable by &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"sorcerer\"&gt;sorcerer&lt;/a&gt; classes.\nGameplay.\nThe caster selects a targeting point on the area map to aim the Comet towards using the targeting cursor.\nWhen spell casting is finished a flaming comet hurtles from above and explodes into a fireball of concussive flame and force from the designated targeting point.\nAll enemy creatures in the area of effect of the impact location are exposed to 10d10 &lt;a href=\"Fire%20damage\"&gt;Fire damage&lt;/a&gt; as well as a &lt;a href=\"Wing%20buffet\"&gt;Wing buffet&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nThe Fire damage can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe blast will move creatures up to 20 feet away from the impact point (it takes 2 seconds duration for this knockback movement), but a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; versus Death/paralysis negates this.\nAdditionally, the same saving throw is required to stem being knocked &lt;a href=\"Unconscious\"&gt;Unconscious&lt;/a&gt; for three rounds by the force of the blast. Elves and half elves do not receive their racial Sleep saving throw resistance for this effect.\nIf a creature fails it's saving throw, additional damage inflicted on the unconscious victim will not awaken them.\nThe \"stunned\" text in the spell's description is actually an unconsciousness effect and the &lt;a href=\"Wing%20buffet\"&gt;knockback&lt;/a&gt; are considered nonmagical effects, meaning they ignore &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; and can't be removed with &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effects. \nThe Comet's internal effects are coded with level 9 &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt;.\nWith the BG2 Enhanced Edition the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt; will not protect against this spell.\nOddly enough, casting this spell over neutral creatures such as inside a populated tavern with no enemies' present will not harm anyone, nor elicit any response.\nTriva.\nThere is no direct equivalent spell to Comet in the Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition ruleset - The Bioware version of the spell appears to have been created just for the BG game.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this High-level class ability spell, revising its casting time, effects, saving throw, school, and description. See below:\nComet\nLevel: Epic\nSchool: Conjuration\nRange: Long\nDuration: Instantaneous\nCasting Time: 1 round\nArea of Effect: 30\u2019 radius\nSaving Throw: Paralyzation partial\nWhen this spell is cast, a huge meteor or comet strikes the earth, damaging all enemies in its path and sending out a powerful shockwave that knocks away all foes in the area of effect. Those caught in the impact suffer 10d10 points of crushing damage and must save vs. paralyzation at -4 or be knocked unconscious for 3 rounds. This spell will not harm party members. Magic resistance does not affect this spell."}
{"id": "55324", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=55324", "title": "Cominda", "text": "Cominda is in the \"employ\" of &lt;a href=\"Madame%20Nin\"&gt;Madame Nin&lt;/a&gt; in the Copper Coronet and will offer services to males as an \"Escort\".\nGameplay.\nSpeak with Madame Nin, and if the party member wishes, he/she may hire a companion for the night for 50 gold. The Madame may call up Cominda to escort you to a room upstairs.\nThe next scene will be the party member and Cominda in a private room.\nShe will initiate dialogue; and more is available based on conversation questions and replies.\nThe player may learn of some illegal slaving going on, and find out that Cominda isn't an employee, but actually forced as a slave escort under Madame Nin's control, and probably approved by Lehtinan the Copper Coronet owner.\nContinue the conversation as desired and spend the night with her if inclined to do so, or leave Cominda with some words of hope, and check into the slavery story later.\nAfter the &lt;a href=\"Free%20Hendak%20and%20the%20slaves\"&gt;Free Hendak and the slaves&lt;/a&gt; questline, if you speak with Cominda again she will have some kind words, and you will learn what Hendak has done for the slave escorts.\nHarming her counts as attacking an innocent, so expect up a -10 &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt; loss if she is killed."}
{"id": "4724", "revid": "283134", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4724", "title": "Command", "text": "Command is a 1st level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt; only usable by &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s. It causes a single creature to sleep for one round.\nGameplay.\nAttack rolls on sleeping enemies always hit and don't cause them to wake up.\nAs this spell inflicts the sleep status effect, &lt;a href=\"elves\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"half-elves\"&gt;half-elves&lt;/a&gt; will naturally have a chance to resist it. This includes characters of level 5 and under, making it one of the few ways to resist this spell at low levels.\nWhile this spell will cause its target (and anyone within the visible range) to aggro, it will prevent NPC's from seeing theft. Thus, it can be used to steal from containers without having the guards called, as long as you don't need to interact with the NPC later. Remember that if the AI is enabled, party members will attack hostile NPCs, possibly causing reputation loss.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this divine spell, revising its effects, scaling, saving throw and description. See below:\nCommand\nLevel: 1\nSchool: Enchantment\nSphere: Charm, Combat, Law\nRange: Long\nDuration: 1 round\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: Spell negates\nThis spell enables the priest to command another creature to lie down and take no action (sleep) for a single round. The creature has a saving throw penalty of -1 (to save against this spell) for every two extra levels of the caster, to a maximum of -4 at 9th level."}
