{"id": "15925", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15925", "title": "Dusty Books", "text": "Dusty Books are fourteen cryptic &lt;a href=\"books\"&gt;books&lt;/a&gt; scattered throughout the &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower%20%28Labyrinth%20Level%20Two%29\"&gt;labyrinth level two&lt;/a&gt; dungeon beneath &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower\"&gt;Durlag's Tower&lt;/a&gt;. Each book consists of notes written by &lt;a href=\"Durlag%20Trollkiller\"&gt;Durlag Trollkiller&lt;/a&gt;. Originally there were sixteen of these books. One of the sixteen books was never included in any edition of the game and a second one is no longer available in the .\nAll of them (except one) are found lying on the floor either near a door, in a passageway, or in a room. Their concise and enigmatic content might hint on things that await behind the door or describe the essence of the passageway or room in which they are located."}
{"id": "32038", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32038", "title": "Dusty Chicken", "text": "The Dusty Chicken is an in \"\".\nAcquisition.\nThe chicken inhabits the &lt;a href=\"Boareskyr%20Bridge\"&gt;Boareskyr Bridge&lt;/a&gt;'s Crusader Camp. It will hop into the inventory of the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; member who talks to it. When the party first enters the camp, it should be somewhere around the area where &lt;a href=\"Delgar%20Munsch\"&gt;Delgar Munsch&lt;/a&gt; is standing, but it's moving around. Despite starting at the camp, there's nothing that limits it from moving anywhere on the map, so it may be difficult to find.\nFunction.\nThe animal can be &lt;a href=\"Boareskyr%20Bridge%23the%20old%20well\"&gt;deposited down a well&lt;/a&gt; in the northwest part of the map on the opposite side of the bridge; your &lt;a href=\"Companions\"&gt;Companions&lt;/a&gt; will &lt;a href=\"Little%20Wanderer%23Quotes\"&gt;comment wittily&lt;/a&gt; about the scenario. After putting the Dusty Chicken in the well you get and the dog &lt;a href=\"BDDOGW01.CRE\"&gt;Little Wander&lt;/a&gt; will appear."}
{"id": "5211", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5211", "title": "Dusty Rose Ioun Stone", "text": "The Dusty Rose Ioun Stone is an ioun stone which offers a +1 bonus to armor class of the wearer.\nIn the EE versions, Ioun Stones no longer protect against critical hits, including this one."}
{"id": "6909", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6909", "title": "Dwarf", "text": "Dwarves are a short but stocky that inhabits &lt;a href=\"Toril\"&gt;Toril&lt;/a&gt;. What a regular dwarf lacks in in height (measuring between 4 and 5 feet), he makes up for in bulk, weighing as much as a mature &lt;a href=\"Human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;. Dwarven males are a bit taller and heavier than their female counterparts.\nDwarves are unusually tough for humanoids, in more ways than one. Dwarven stomachs, for instance, are resistant to virtually all poisons and it takes less effort for a dwarf to get back on their feet than other races. Dwarves also have dense bodies and are difficult to push around as a result, as well as having the capacity to bear loads, that other races might find hindering, with little ill effect.\nMale dwarves are often bald and grow thick facial hair, which is sometimes used to display social status. Unusually for humanoids, both sexes naturally grow ample facial hair, though the majority of shield dwarf females shave their beards off.\nMany dwarves have an affinity for the caverns in which they live, possessing a knack for recognizing unusual patterns in stonework that could almost seem supernatural at times. They are also renowned for their metalworking and crafting abilities.\nSubraces.\nDuergar.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Duergar\"&gt;Duergar&lt;/a&gt;, also known as gray dwarves, are a subterranean subrace of dwarves. They carve out an existence in the &lt;a href=\"Underdark\"&gt;Underdark&lt;/a&gt;. Their kinship to surface dwarves can be compared to that of the &lt;a href=\"Drow\"&gt;Drow&lt;/a&gt; to surface &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elf&lt;/a&gt; folk. Duergar are implemented in the game.\nGold Dwarf.\nGold dwarves, are a subterranean subrace of dwarves, and are known for their confidence and keen intuition. The culture of their Deep Kingdom values family, ritual, and fine craftmanship. These are not implemented in the game.\nShield Dwarf.\nShield Dwarves, are a subterranean subrace of dwarves, survived a long fall from grace, surrendering many of their ancient kingdoms in wars with goblins and orcs. These losses have lead to a cynical mindset, yet shield dwarves will endure anything to restore their ancestral homelands. These are not implemented in the game.\nClasses.\nClass Accessibility.\n&lt;a href=\"Barbarian\"&gt;Barbarian&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;Cleric&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Thief\"&gt;Thief&lt;/a&gt;\nMulti-Class Accessibility.\n&lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Fighter / Thief&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Cleric\"&gt;Fighter / Cleric&lt;/a&gt;\nDwarves make excellent warriors because of their extremely high constitution. The very small selection of playable classes available for dwarves, second only to &lt;a href=\"halfling\"&gt;halfling&lt;/a&gt;s, may discourage anyone wanting to play a dwarf that isn't the fighting type. They don't have as much strength as &lt;a href=\"half-orc\"&gt;half-orc&lt;/a&gt;s, but their ungodly high saving throws more than makes up for it in the long run. While the 17 maximum in dexterity at character creation hurts their armor class, it can be boosted to 18 with the use of skill manuals. This will put your &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;AC&lt;/a&gt; on par with any other race outside of halflings and &lt;a href=\"elf\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt;. Dwarves are also the only race who can play as the fighter kit &lt;a href=\"Dwarven%20Defender\"&gt;Dwarven Defender&lt;/a&gt;, which is the only class kit that is not available to &lt;a href=\"Human\"&gt;humans&lt;/a&gt;.\nThose interested in playing &lt;a href=\"thief\"&gt;thieves&lt;/a&gt; can still do so with a dwarf character because the dexterity restriction is actually balanced out by naturally high racial adjustments to thieving skills (particularly disarm traps, open locks and set traps). However, it should be noted that the high constitution bonus only applies to warrior classes and the steep charisma penalty dwarves suffer doesn't make them ideal as party leaders or for getting the best prices at stores.\nIn-Game Depiction.\nThe games lack a female sprite for the dwarven race. As such, there is no visual difference between female and male dwarves.\nRelated Items.\nExclusive item: &lt;a href=\"Dwarven%20Thrower\"&gt;Dwarven Thrower&lt;/a&gt; \nNot exclusive items but better for Dwarves :"}
{"id": "49383", "revid": "50459896", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49383", "title": "Dwarf Thrall", "text": "The Dwarf Thrall is a &lt;a href=\"thief\"&gt;thief&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; and one of only two thralls who does not have a &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Collar\"&gt;Thrall Collar&lt;/a&gt;. He is found &lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;hiding in the shadows&lt;/a&gt; behind the &lt;a href=\"Master%20of%20Thralls\"&gt;Master of Thralls&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter the Master is dead, he emerges from the shadows, amazed at the party.\"You...you have killed the master! You have killed him!! By Clangeddin's Axe, I thought such a thing not even possible!\"He can then answer a few questions:\nIf quick enough (now equipped with the &lt;a href=\"The%20Paws%20of%20the%20Cheetah\"&gt;The Paws of the Cheetah&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href=\"Bounty%20Hunter%20%28Planar%20Prison%20Thief%29\"&gt;halfling bounty hunter&lt;/a&gt;), he can be pick-pocketed for &lt;a href=\"Random%20treasure%23Well-off%20treasure\"&gt;well-off random treasure&lt;/a&gt; before he disappears.\n\"I...I must flee before the Warden discovers the Master of Thralls is dead! Please...destroy the orb if you are able! I beg of you!!\""}
